Notice of Opposition to Claim of Exemption
Notice of Hearing on Claim of Exemption
Notice of Hearing on Right to Homestead Exemption
Notice of Rehearing on Right to Homestead Exemption
Notice of Lien
Application for and Renewal of Judgment
Notice of Renewal of Judgment
Expedited Jury Trial Information Sheet
Request to Opt Out of Mandatory Expedited Jury Trial Procedures
Objection to Request to Opt Out of Mandatory Expedited Jury Trial Procedures
Agreement of Parties (Mandatory Expedited Jury Trial Procedures)
[Proposed] Consent Order for Voluntary Expedited Jury Trial
Attachment to [Proposed] Consent OrderOr Agreemetn of Parties
Petition for Declaration of Emancipation of Minor, Order Prescribing Notice, Declaration of Emancipation, and Order Denying Petition
Emancipation Pamphlet
Notice of Hearing—Emancipation of Minor
Emancipation of Minor Income and Expense Declaration
Declaration of Emancipation of Minor After Hearing
Emancipated Minor's Application to California Department of Motor Vehicles
Emergency Protective Order (CLETS-EPO)
Gun Violence Emergency Protective Order (CLETS-EGV)
Petition—Marriage/Domestic Partnership (Family Law)
column4: Start a divorce, legal separation, or annulment case if you are married, registered domestic partners, or both.  This identifies all the issues you want to include in a judgment.

column1: Declaration Under Uniform Child Custody Jurisdiction and Enforcement Act (UCCJEA)
Attachment to Declaration Under Uniform Child Custody Jurisdiction and Enforcement Act (UCCJEA)
Legal Steps for a Divorce or Legal Separation
column4: Explains the steps to begin and complete a case for divorce or legal separation. It includes links to online resources to help understand each step in the process.

column1: Summons
column4: Tells your spouse or domestic partner that a court case has started, your rights and responsibilities, and what can happen if a response is not filed in 30 days.

column1: Proof of Service of Summons (Family Law-Uniform Parentage-Custody and Support)
column4: Tells the court that you had your spouse or domestic partner served with the legal papers to start your case. Tells when and where the papers were served, and who served them.

column1: Notice and Acknowledgment of Receipt
column4: Tell the court that your spouse or domestic partner agreed to (and received) by mail the legal papers to start your case.

column1: Response—Marriage/Domestic Partnership (Family Law)
column4: Tell the court and your spouse or domestic partner that you are responding to the summons and petition and describe the orders you want the court to make in the case.

column1: Appearance, Stipulations, and Waivers (Family Law—Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
column4: Tell the court that you and your spouse or domestic partner want the court to approve your written agreement or stipulated judgment without going to court for a trial.

column1: Declaration and Conditional Waiver of Rights Under the Servicemembers Civil Relief Act of 2003
column4: Tell the court you are a servicemember on active duty and you want the court to enter your settlement agreement or stipulated judgment in your absence.

column1: Declaration of Disclosure
column4: List all the financial documents and information on this cover page that you give (disclose) to your spouse or domestic partner as part of the first or final set of disclosure documents.

column1: Declaration Regarding Service of Declaration of Disclosure and Income and Expense Declaration
column4: Tell the court that you had the first or final set of financial documents served on your spouse or domestic partner.

column1: Schedule of Assets and Debts
column4: List all your known property and debt. This can be used as an attachment to Declaration of Disclosure (form FL-140) or you may use Property Declaration (form FL-160) instead.

column1: Stipulation and Waiver of Final Declaration of Disclosure
column4: Tell the court that you and your spouse or domestic partner exchanged the preliminary (first) declaration of disclosure and agree not to exchange the final declaration of disclosure documents with each other.

column1: Form Interrogatories—Family Law
column4: Tell your spouse or domestic partner to answer specific questions and give documents before trial.

column1: Income and Expense Declaration
column4: Give your financial information to the court and to your spouse or domestic partner.  The court uses the information to make orders for support, attorneys fees, and other costs.

column1: Financial Statement (Simplified)
column4: Give your financial information to the court and to your spouse or domestic partner. This also explains when to use either this form or form FL-150. The court considers the information before making child support orders.

column1: Spousal or Domestic Partner Support Declaration Attachment
column4: Explain the facts that support your request for a spousal or domestic partner support judgment. This is always attached to another form, like Declaration for Default or Uncontested Judgment (Form FL-170)

column1: Supporting Declaration for Attorney's Fees and Costs Attachment
column4: Explain why the court should or should not order you or your spouse or domestic partner to pay attorneys fees and costs. This is always attached to Request for Attorney's Fees and Costs Attachment (form FL-319) or Responsive Declaration (form FL-320).

column1: Property Declaration
column4: List your property and debts and how you would like to divide them. This can be used as an attachment to Declaration of Disclosure (form FL-140) or you may use Schedule of Assets and Debts (form FL-142) instead.

column1: Continuation of Property Declaration
column4: Give more details about your property and debts and attach to Property Declaration (form FL-160)

column1: Request to Enter Default (Uniform Parentage)
column4: Ask the court for a decision (order) that time has ended for your spouse or domestic partner to file a response to your petition. This allows you to ask the court for a judgment based on a signed settlement agreement or, if no agreement, based on what you asked for in the petition.

column1: Declaration for Default or Uncontested Dissolution or Legal Separation (Family Law)
column4: Tell the court more about your request to enter a judgment based on an agreement or the default of your spouse or domestic partner.

column1: Case Information—Family Law
column4: Used by courts to specify important issues in a family law case.

column1: Family Centered Case Resolution Order
column4: Used by courts to provide a record of decisions made during a family centered case resolution conference.

column1: Judgment
column4: The first pages of the final orders for your divorce, legal separation, or annulment case. You or your attorney complete the first page and use attachments for other final orders, like child custody and visitation, child support, spousal or domestic partner support, property division, attorneys fees, and other orders.

column1: Judgment Checklist—Dissolution/Legal Separation
column4: This cover page lists the documents you give to the court to ask for a default or uncontested judgment.

column1: Notice of Entry of Judgment (Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
column4: Lists the type of judgment that the court made (granted), like divorce, legal separation, or annulment. It also states the date that your legal relationship changed and the date that the court entered the judgment.

column1: Child Support Case Registry Form
column4: Give information to the court about the child support or family support order in your case.

column1: Notice of Rights and Responsibilities (Health-Care Costs and Reimbursement Procedures)
column4: Explains how to ask the other parent to help pay for your child's health care cost that is not covered by insurance. It also describes how to change a child support order.

column1: Income Withholding for Support
column4: Tells an employer that the court made an order for you or the other person in the case to pay child support, medical support, spousal or domestic partner support (and any past-due support). The order tells the employer how much money to take out of the employee's pay check, how often to take out the money, and where to send it. This is also known as a wage assignment.

column1: Income Withholding for Support—Instructions
column4: Explains how to fill out Income Withholding for Support (form FL-195). Also includes information for the employer.

column1: Petition to Determine Parental Relationship (Uniform Parentage)
column4: Start a case to get a court order (judgment) that identifies the legal parents of a child. This is used by parents who are not married.

column1: Summons (Uniform Parentage—Petition for Custody and Support) (incl. Spanish)
column4: Tells the other parent of the child that a court case has started and what will happen if the other parent's response is not filed in 30 days.

column1: Response to Petition to Determine Parental Relationship (Uniform Parentage)
column4: Tell the court and your spouse or domestic partner that you are responding to the summons and petition and describe the orders that you want the court to make in the case.

column1: Declaration for Default or Uncontested Judgment (Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
column4: Use this with Request for Default (form FL-165) to ask the court for a decision (order) that time has ended for the other parent to file a response to your petition. This allows you to ask the court for a judgment based on a signed settlement agreement or, if no agreement, based on what you asked for in the petition.

column1: Advisement and Waiver of Rights Re: Determination of Parental Relationship (Uniform Parentage)
column4: Tell the court that you and the other parent have an agreement to establish parentage and that you agree to give up the rights listed in the form so that the court can approve the Judgment (form FL-250) without a trial.

column1: Stipulation for Entry of Judgment Re: Determination of Parental Relationship
column4: This is the first page of the agreement you have with the child's other parent about establishing parentage, child custody and visitation (parenting time), child support, and other matters.

column1: Judgment (Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
column4: The first pages of the final orders (judgment) that establish the legal parents of the child. You or your attorney complete this and use attachments for other final orders, like child custody and visitation, (parenting time). child support, and others.

column1: Petition for Custody and Support of Minor Children
Response to Petition for Custody and Support of Minor Children
column4: Tell the court and the petitioner that you are responding to the summons and petition and describe the orders that you want the court to make in the case.

column1: Notice of Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage
column4: Tell the court and the other parent that you want a hearing to ask the court to cancel all the orders included in the judgment of parentage. Also ask the court to order genetic testing and enter a judgment stating that you are not the child's parent.

column1: Declaration in Support of Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage (Family Law - Governmental)
column4: Give more information about your request to cancel a judgment of parentage. This must be attached to Notice of Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage (form FL-272).

column1: Information Sheet for Completing Notice of Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage
column4: Explains who can ask the court to cancel a judgment of parentage, what forms are needed, and desribes the time frame for the filing.

column1: Response to Notice of Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage
column4: Tell the court and the other sides if you agree or disagree with the orders the other side asked for in Notice of Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage (form FL-272).  Also give facts to support your response.

column1: Order After Hearing on Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Judgment of Parentage (Family Law - Governmental)
column4: States the court's decision (an order) about the request to cancel (set aside) a judgment of parentage.

column1: Request for Hearing and Application to Cancel (Set Aside) Voluntary Declaration of Parentage or Paternity
column4: Tell the court and the other parties that you want a hearing to ask the court to cancel (set aside) the voluntary declaration of parentage or paternity. This is also used by the court to set the date, time, and location of the hearing.

column1: Information Sheet for Completing Request for Hearing and Application to Cancel (Set Aside) Voluntary Declaration of Parentage or Paternity (Family Law - Governmental)
column4: Explains how to complete Request for Hearing and Application to Cancel (Set Aside) Voluntary Declaration of Parentage or Paternity (form FL-280) and describes the timeframe for filing the form.

column1: Responsive Declaration to Application to Cancel (Set Aside) Voluntary Declaration of Parentage or Paternity
column4: Tell the court and the other parties if you agree or disagree with the orders the other party asked for in Request for Hearing on Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Voluntary Declaration of Parentage (form FL-280). Also give facts to support your response.

column1: Order After Hearing on Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Voluntary Declaration of Parentage or Paternity (Family Law - Governmental)
column4: States the court's decision (an order) about the request to cancel (set aside) a voluntary declaration of parentage or paternity.

column1: Request for Order
column4: Ask the court to make decisions (orders) about specific issues in your family law case. This is also used by the court to set the date, time, and location of the hearing.

column1: Information Sheet for Request for Order (Family Law)
column4: Explains how to fill out Request for Order (form FL-300) to ask the court to make decisions (orders) in your family law case. It includes: steps to get a hearing date on the court's regular calendar or ask for emergency orders, information about serving the papersparty served, and resources if you have questions or need legal help.

column1: Declaration Regarding Notice and Service of Request for Temporary Emergency (Ex Parte) Orders
column4: Tells the court if and how you let the other party know that you are asking the court to make emergency orders in your case. You can also use the form to ask the court to order that notice is not needed before the court makes emergency orders.

column1: How to Reschedule a Hearing in Family Court
Temporary Emergency (Ex Parte) Orders
column4: States the court's decision (order) when a party asked for temporary emergency orders.

column1: Request to Reschedule Hearing (Family Law—Governmental—Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
column4: Ask to change your hearing date and explain why you need a new hearing date.

column1: Request to Reschedule Hearing Involving Temporary Emergency (Ex Parte) Orders (Family Law—Governmental—Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
column4: States the court's decision (order) when a party asked to change a hearing date.

column1: Agreement and Order to Reschedule Hearing (Family Law—Governmental—Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
Order on Request to Reschedule Hearing (Family Law—Governmental—Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
Responsive Declaration to Request to Reschedule Hearing (Family Law—Governmental—Uniform Parentage—Custody and Support)
Child Custody and Visitation (Parenting Time) Application Attachment
column4: Give the court and the other party more details about the orders you want the court to make about child custody and visitation (parenting time).

column1: Request for Child Abduction Prevention Orders
column4: Tell the court why you are worried that the other parent might kidnap your child and ask for orders to try to prevent that from happening.

column1: Child Custody Information Sheet—Recommending Counseling
column4: Explains that some family courts use child custody recommending counseling (CCRC) to help parents create a parening plan agreement before the court makes orders about child custody and visitation. This form also explains the next steps if parents do not agree on a parenting plan during CCRC and includes information about how to find help.

column1: Child Custody Information Sheet—Child Custody Mediation
column4: Explains that family courts uses mediation to help parents create their own parenting plan agreement before the court makes orders about child custody and visitation. This form also explains the next steps if parents do not agree on a parenting plan and includes information about how to find help.

column1: Request or Response to Request for Separate Trial
column4: Ask the court for a trial to decide one important issue before all other issues in your case. This can also be used to respond to a request for separate trial.

column1: Request for Orders Regarding Noncompliance With Disclosure Requirements
column4: Tell the court that you gave the other party a complete declaration of disclosure as required by law, but the other party did not do the same. Then, list the orders that you want the court to make. This form is always attached to Request for Order (form FL-300).

column1: Retirement Plan Joinder—Information Sheet
column4: Lists different types of retirement plans and tells you if the plan, by law, needs to be joined (made a party to the case) before the court makes orders that change your legal status and divide the retirement plan.

column1: Request for Attorney's Fees and Costs Attachment
column4: Give the court and the other party more details about the order for attorney's fees that you are asking the court to make.

column1: Responsive Declaration to Request for Order
column4: Tell the court and the other party if you agree or disagree with the orders the other party asked for in Request for Order (form FL-300).  Also describe the orders you want the court to make instead of those that the other party asked for.

column1: Information Sheet: Responsive Declaration to Request for Order
column4: Explains how to complete Responsive Declaration to Request for Order (form FL-320), file, and have it served.

column1: Witness List
column4: Ask the court to allow each person that you list to testify (give evidence in person) at a hearing or trial.  You must also describe what each person is expected to say to the court.

column1: Declaration of Counsel for a Child Regarding Qualifications
column4: Tells you and the court that the lawyer is qualified to represent a child in the case. This is used by a lawyer to specify the licenses, professional liability insurance, education and training, experience, annual continuing education that satsify the requirements for appointment.

column1: Order Appointing Counsel for a Child
column4: States the court's decision (an order) to appoint a lawyer for your child. Also states the lawyer's rights and responsibilities and how the lawyer will be paid.

column1: Attorney for Child in a Family Law Case—Information Sheet
column4: This answers general questions about lawyers appointed for a child in a family law case.  Questions include: What will the lawyer do?  Who pays the lawyer?  How long will the lawyer represent the child?

column1: Declaration of Supervised Visitation Provider (Professional)
column4: Tells you and the court that the person is eligible to be appointed by the court as a paid (professional) or unpaid (nonprofessional) supervised visitation provider. This lists the provider's specific qualifications and says that the person satisfies the appointment requirements.

column1: Declaration of Supervised Visitation Provider (NonProfessional)
Declaration of Court-connected Child Custody Evaluator Regarding Qualifications
column4: Tells you and the court that the person is a court employee who is eligible to be appointed to as a child custody evaluator.  This is used to list the employee's specific qualifications before the court orders the appointment.

column1: Declaration of Private Child Custody Evaluator Regarding Qualifications
column4: Tells you and the court that the person is a private professional who is eligible to be appointed as a child custody evaluator.  This is used to list the person's specific qualifications before the court orders the appointment.

column1: Order Appointing Child Custody Evaluator
column4: States the court's decision (an order) to appoint a licensed psychologist, marriage and family therapist, clinical social worker, or psychiatrist to investigate and make recommendations about child custody and visitation orders that are in your child's best interest.

column1: Additional Orders Regarding Child Custody Evaluations Under Family Code Section 3118
Notice Regarding Confidentiality of Child Custody Evaluation Report
column4: The child custody evaluator uses this as the first page of the written recommendations for child custody and a parenting plan in your case. This explains that the recommendation must be kept confidential, lists the exceptions to confidentiality, and warns about penalties for disclosing the report against the child's best interests.

column1: Confidential Child Custody Evaluation Report
Child Custody Evaluation Information Sheet
column4: Gives general information to parents when the court appoints a child custody evaluator to make recommendations about a parenting plan that is in the child's best interest.

column1: Proof of Personal Service
column4: Tells the court that you had the other party served in person with legal papers.  Lists the papers that were served. It also tells when and where the papers were served and who served them.

column1: Information Sheet for Proof of Personal Service
column4: Explains who can serve legal documents and how to complete Proof of Personal Service (form FL-330)

column1: Declaration Regarding Address Verification—Postjudgment Request to Modify a Child Custody, Visitation, or Child Support Order
column4: Tells the court that you are certain of the address where the other parent lives and that you had the other parent served by mail at that address with a Request for Order (form FL-300) to change a judgment or permanent orders for child custody, visitation, or child support. This is used as an attachment to a proof of service by mail.

column1: Proof of Service by Mail
column4: Tells the court that you had the other party served legal papers by mail.  Lists the papers that were served and tells when and where the papers were served, as well as who served them.

column1: Information Sheet for Proof of Service by Mail
column4: Explains how to complete Proof of Service by Mail (form FL-335). Also explains who can serve legal papers by mail and which legal papers cannot be served by mail.

column1: Order to Pay Waived Court Fees and Costs (Superior Court)
column4: States the court's decision (an order) that a party must pay back the initial fees that the court previously waived (said that the party did not have to pay). Also explains how to ask the court to continue to waive those fees.

column1: Application to Set Aside Order to Pay Waived Court Fees—Attachment
column4: Tell the court and the other person in your case that you want the court to continue the order to waive the initial fees in your case. This form is always attached to Request for Order (form FL-300).

column1: Order After Hearing on Motion to Set Aside Order to Pay Waived Court Fees (Superior Court)
column4: States the court's decision (an order) when a party asks the court to continue waiving the initial fees in the family law case.

column1: Findings and Order After Hearing
column4: This is used as the first page to list the decisions (orders) that a court made after a hearing. The orders are generally attached to this page.

column1: Child Custody and Visitation (Parenting Time) Order Attachment
column4: States the court's decisions (orders) after a hearing about child custody and visitation (parenting time) plans that are in the child's best interest. This can be used as an attachment to many other forms, as noted at the top of form FL-341.

column1: Supervised Visitation Order
column4: States the court's decisions (orders) after a hearing about supervised visitation (parenting time) or supervised exchanges. This is attached to Child Custody and Visitation (Parenting Time) Order Attachment (form FL-341).

column1: Child Abduction Prevention Order Attachment
column4: States the court's decisions (order) after a hearing on whether a child is at risk of being kidnapped by a parent. The orders are generally attached to Child Custody and Visitation (Parenting Time) Order Attachment (form FL-341) or Custody Order--Juvenile--Final Judgment (form JV-200).

column1: Children's Holiday Schedule Attachment
column4: This can be used as an attachment to many forms. Parents can use the form to describe the holiday parenting plan believed to be in the child's best interests. It can also be used to state the family or juvenile court's decisions (orders) about the child's holiday parenting plan after a hearing.

column1: Additional Provisions—Physical Custody Attachment
column4: This can be used as an attachment to many forms.  Parents can use the form to make agreements, or request court orders, about other matters concerning child custody that are in the child's best interest. It can also be used to state family or juvenile court's decisions (orders) about additional child custody issues.

column1: Joint Legal Custody Attachment
column4: This can be used as an attachment to many forms.  Parents can use the form to make agreements, or request court orders, about how parents will exercise joint legal custody in the child's best interest. It can also be used to state the family or juvenile court's decisions (orders) about additional child custody issues.

column1: Child Support Information and Order Attachment
column4: States the court's decisions (orders) about child support. This can be attached to many other forms, including Findings and Order After Hearing (form FL-340), Judgments (forms FL-180 and FL-250), and Restraining Order After Hearing (form DV -130).

column1: Non-Guideline Support Findings Attachment
column4: States the court's reasons why it decided (ordered), or the parent's agreed to, child support payments  that are below or above the statewide child support guidelines. This is generally attached to Child Support Information and Order Attachment (form FL-342) or Judgment (form FL-180).

column1: Spousal, Domestic Partner, or Family Support Order Attachment
column4: States the court's decision (order or judgment), or the parties' agreement, about spousal, domestic partner, or family support.

column1: Property Order Attachment to Findings and Order After Hearing
column4: States the court's decisions (orders) about the parties' assets and debts. This is attached to Findings and Order After Hearing (form FL-340).

column1: Property Order Attachment to Judgment
column4: States the court's decisions about the division of the parties' assets and debts. This is attached to a judgment.

column1: Attorney's Fees and Costs Order Attachment
column4: States the court's decision (an order) about who will pay attorney's fees and cost, the amount of each payment, and when payments are due. This is attached to Findings and Order After Hearing (form FL-340), Judgment (form FL-180 or FL-250), or another document.

column1: Bifurcation of Status of Marriage or Domestic Partnership—Attachment
column4: States the court's decisions (orders) about the date the parties are to become legally single and other orders that are connected to the change of legal status.

column1: Pension Benefits—Attachment to Judgment (Attach to form FL-180)
column4: Tells the pension plan administrator that court made temporary orders about the pension until a final order (a qualified domestic relations order) is completed.  Explains what parties need to do to protect their interest in the pension.

column1: Spousal or Domestic Partner Support Factors Under Family Code Section 4320—Attachment
Stipulation to Establish or Modify Child Support and Order
column4: Parents tell the court about their agreement to make an initial (the first) order for child support or modify (change) existing orders. The court also uses this to make their agreement a court order.

column1: Stipulation and Order for Custody and/or Visitation of Children
column4: Parents tell the court that they have an agreement about child custody and visitation (parenting time) and that the agreement is attach to the form. The court also uses this to make their agreement a  court order.

column1: Confidential Request for Special Immigrant Juvenile Findings—Family Law
column4: Tell the court and the other sides that you are asking the court for a hearing to give you sole physical custody of the child and make certain findings (conclusions) about the child. Give the court information and documents to support your request for the court to make findings about child custody and make other findings that state (1) it is not legally possible to return the child to the other parent due to abuse, neglect, abandonment, or another legal reason and (2) it is not in the child's best interest to return to the parent's or the child's country of nationality or habitual residence.

column1: Special Immigrant Juvenile Findings
column4: States the court's findings (conclusions) after considering facts and evidence included with a Confidential Request for Special Immigrant Juvenile Findings (form FL-355)

column1: Confidential Response to Request for Special Immigrant Juvenile Findings
column4: Tell the court and the other side if you agree or disagree with the findings that the other side requested in form FL-356.  Also,if applicable, describe the findings that you would want the court to make instead of those that the other side asked for.

column1: Request for Hearing and Application to Set Aside Support Order Under Family Code Section 3691
column4: Tell the court and the other side that the court should dismiss ("set-aside") an order that requires you to pay support. The grounds for setting aside a support order are: fraud, perjury, or lack of notice. You must also file the request by the time specified in the form.

column1: Responsive Declaration to Application to Set Aside Support Order
column4: Tell the court and the other side if you agree to dismiss (set-aside) the support order and give your reasons.

column1: Order After Hearing on Motion to Set Aside Support Order
column4: States the court's decision (an order) after a hearing about a party's request to dismiss ("set-aside") a support order based on fraud, perjury, or lack of notice.

column1: Pleading on Joinder—Employees Benefit Plan
column4: Tells an employee benefit plan administrator that the plan has been made a claiment (a party) to the court case.

column1: Notice of Motion and Declaration for Joinder
column4: Ask the court to decide (order) to make you a party in the family law case. This is commonly used by a grandparent or a step-parent who wants to participate in the case concerning child custody and visitation (parenting time).

column1: Request for Joinder of Employee Benefit Plan Order
column4: Tell the court that you want an order for the administrator of an employee benefit plan to become party in the case. Other forms needed in this process are described in

column1: Responsive Declaration to Motion for Joinder and Consent Order of Joinder
column4: Tell the court if you agree with the request that a person be made a party in the family law case, as described in Notice of Motion and Declaration for Joinder (form FL-370).

column1: Notice of Appearance and Response of Employee Benefit Plan
column4: The employee benefit plan administrator uses this to respond to the the request to be joined in the family law case.

column1: Summons (Joinder)
column4: Tells the administrators of an employee benefit plan that they are named as a claimant (a party) in a family law case and what will happen if a response is not filed in 30 days.

column1: Application for Expedited Child Support Order
column4: Tell the other parent that you want the court to order that parent to pay a specific amount of child support until trial. Tells you all other forms that are needed in this process.

column1: Response to Application for Expedited Child Support Order and Notice of Hearing
column4: The other parent responds to a request for an expedited chld support order. If applicable, includes details about a hearing before the court makes an order.

column1: Expedited Child Support Order
column4: States the court's decision (order) about a request for an expedited child support order.

column1: Notice of Motion and Motion for Simplified Modification of Order for Child, Spousal, or Family Support
column4: Tell the other parent (or party) details about a hearing to ask the court to change an order for child support, spousal or domestic partner support, or family support. Explains what other forms need to be complete and how to serve the documents on the other parent.

column1: Information Sheet—Simplified Way to Change Child, Spousal, or Family Support
column4: Explains how to use a simplified process to ask the court to change a child, spousal or domestic partner, or a family support order.

column1: Responsive Declaration to Motion for Simplified Modification of Order for Child, Spousal, or Family Support
column4: Tell the court and the other party if you agree or disagree with the request to change a child support. spousal or domestic partner support, or family support order using a simplified process.

column1: Information Sheet—How to Oppose a Request to Change Child, Spousal, or Family Support
column4: Explains how to tell the court and the other parent (or party) that you disagree with the request to change orders for child, spousal or domestic partner, or family support.

column1: Ex Parte Application for Restoration of Former Name After Entry of Judgment and Order
column4: Tell the court that a judgment for divorce or nullity was entered and now you want an order to let you legally use name you had before you married or registered the domestic partnership.

column1: Request for Production of an Income and Expense Declaration After Judgment
column4: Ask the other party (your former spouse or domestic partner) to give you current financial information after the court entered a judgment in your case.

column1: Request for Income and Benefit Information From Employer
column4: Ask the employer of your former spouse or domestic partner to give you information about employment status and wages if you did not receive a response using form FL-396 or the response received was incomplete.

column1: Notice of Activation of Military Service and Deployment and Request to Modify a Support Order
column4: Tell that court and the other parent that you are a military service member, you have been activated to duty, deployed out of state, and you want to change a child support order.

column1: Order for Child Support Security Deposit and Evidence of Deposit
column4: Tells the person that owes child support that they have to deposit money as security for future child support. It also tells the judge that the money was put in a bank account.

column1: Application for Disbursement and Order for Disbursement From Child Support Security Deposit
column4: Ask the judge to give you money put in the bank as security for future child support by the other parent. It also tells the bank to give the money to you.

column1: Order to Show Cause and Affidavit for Contempt
column4: Ask the judge to punish the other parent for violating the judge's orders.

column1: Affidavit of Facts Constituting Contempt (Financial and Injunctive Orders)
column4: Give the judge information about how the other side violated the support order and attach to Order to Show Cause and Affidavit for Contempt (form FL-410).

column1: Affidavit of Facts Constituting Contempt (Domestic Violence/Custody and Visitation)
column4: Give the judge information about how the other side violated the restraining order, custody and visitation order, or other orders and attach to Order to Show Cause and Affidavit for Contempt (form FL-410).

column1: Findings and Order Regarding Contempt (Domestic Violence —Uniform Parentage—Governmental)
column4: States the judge's decision after a contempt trial or hearing.

column1: Declaration of Payment History (Governmental—Uniform Parentage Act)
column4: Tells the court and the other parent how much support you believe has been paid in your case.

column1: Payment History Attachment (Governmental—Uniform Parentage Act)
column4: Gives a monthly breakdown about how much support has been paid and attach to Declaration of Payment History (form FL-420).

column1: Ex Parte Application to Issue, Modify, or Terminate an Earnings Assignment Order
column4: Ask the judge to change or stop an order for support to taken out of the paycheck of a parent, spouse, or partner.

column1: Earnings Assignment Order for Spousal or Partner Support
column4: Tells an employer that the court made an order for spousal or partner support . The order tells the employer how much money to take out of the employee's paycheck and where to send it.

column1: Statement for Registration of California Support Order
column4: Tells you that your support order was moved (registered) to the court of a different county.

column1: Request for Hearing Regarding Registration of California Support Order (Family Law-Governmental)
column4: Ask the judge to cancel moving (registering) your support order to the court of a different county.

column1: Request for Hearing Regarding Earnings Assignment (Governmental—UIFSA)
column4: Ask the judge to cancel the order for support to be taken out of your paycheck.

column1: Stay of Service of Earnings Assignment and Order
column4: Ask the judge to stop the order for child, spousal, or partner support to be taken out of your paycheck. Ask the judge to order that support be taken out of the other side's paycheck, if the judge stopped the order before. Tells you that the judge stopped or restarted the order for support to be taken out of the paycheck of the other parent, spouse, or partner.

column1: Qualified Domestic Relations Order for Support (Earnings Assignment Order for Support)
column4: Tells you that the judge ordered child, spousal, or partner support to be taken out of the retirement plan of the other parent, spouse, or partner once a month.

column1: Attachment to Qualified Domestic Relations Order for Support (Earnings Assignment Order for Support)
column4: Tells the retirement plan information about the employee and the person receiving spousal or partner support. It is attached to Qualified Domestice Relations Order for Support (form FL-460), but is not filed with the court.

column1: Application And Order For Health Insurance Coverage
column4: Ask the judge to make the employer of a parent include the children in their health insurance coverage. It also tells the employer to include the children in the health insurance.

column1: Employer's Health Insurance Return
column4: Gives the judge and the parents information about health insurance coverage available to the employee.

column1: Request and Notice of Hearing Regarding Health Insurance Assignment
column4: Ask the judge to change or stop an order for health insurance coverage for the children.

column1: Information Sheet and Instructions for Request and Notice of Hearing Regarding Health Insurance Assignment
column4: Explains how to ask the judge to change or stop an order for health insurance coverage for the children.

column1: Abstract of Support Judgment
column4: Tells you that a lien can be placed on any real property (like a house) that you own now or in the future, as long as you owe support.

column1: Notice of Delinquency
column4: Tells the person that owes child support that they are more than 30 days late in making payments.

column1: Application to Determine Arrears
column4: Ask the judge to figure out how much back support is owed. It must be attached to Request for Order (form FL-300).

column1: Summons (UIFSA)
column4: Tells one of the parents that a child support case from another state has started and what can happen if a response is not filed in 30 days.

column1: Response to Uniform Support Petition (UIFSA)
column4: Tell the judge and the other parent that you are responding to and describe the orders you want the judge to make in the case.

column1: Judgment Regarding Parental Obligations (UIFSA)
column4: States the decision of the judge in a child support case from another state.

column1: Ex Parte Application for Transfer and Order (UIFSA)
column4: Ask the judge to move (transfer) your support order from California to a different state. It also tells the court clerk to move (transfer) your support order to a different state.

column1: Notice of Registration of Out-of-State Support Order
column4: Tells you that your support order was moved (registered) from a different state to California.

column1: Request for Hearing Regarding Registration of Out-Of-State Support Order
column4: Ask the judge to cancel moving (registering) your support order from a different state to California.

column1: Registration of Out-of-State Custody Order
column4: Ask the judge to move (register) your child custody order from a different state to California.

column1: Request for Hearing Regarding Registration of Out-of-State Custody Decree
column4: Ask the judge to cancel moving (registering) your child custody order from a different state to California.

column1: UIFSA Child Support Order Jurisdictional Attachment
column4: States the judge's decision why your suppport order was moved (registered) from a different state to California.

column1: Notice of Registration of an International Hague Convention Support Order
column4: Tells you that your support order was moved (registered) from a different country to California.

column1: Request for Heaing Regarding Registration of an International Hague Convention Support Order
column4: Ask the judge to cancel moving (registering) your support order from a different country to California.

column1: Summons and Complaint or Supplemental Complaint Regarding Parental Obligations (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency opened up a case asking that you be named the parent, pay child support, and provide health insurance for the child listed.

column1: Notice and Acknowledgment of Receipt
column4: Tell the judge that you agreed to accept delivery of the child support papers by mail.

column1: Answer to Complaint or Supplemental Complaint Regarding Parental Obligations (Governmental)
column4: Tell the judge and the local child support agency if you agree that you are the parent or agree to pay the requested amount of child support.

column1: Information Sheet for Service of Process
column4: Explains how to complete a proof of service form.

column1: Stipulation for Judgment or Supplemental Judgment Regarding Parental Obligations and Judgment (Governmental)
column4: Parents and the local child support agency tell the court about their agreement to name the parents of the child and for child support.

column1: Declaration for Amended Proposed Judgment (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency wants to change how much child support you should pay.

column1: Request for Dismissal (Governmental, UIFSA)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency is canceling the case against you.

column1: Request to Enter Default Judgment (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency is asking for a child support order without your participation because you didn't file an answer.

column1: Stipulation and Order (Governmental)
column4: Parents and the local child support agency tell the court about their agreement for child support.

column1: Stipulation and Order Waiving Unassigned Arrears (Governmental)
column4: Parents and the local child support agency tell the court about their agreement for back child support.

column1: Order for Genetic (Parentage) Testing
column4: Tells you that the judge ordered you to get genetic tests to see if you are the parent of the child.

column1: Judgment Regarding Parental Obligations (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the judge named the legal parents of the child and made a child support order. If it's "proposed" it means the judge hasn't approved it yet.

column1: Notice Regarding Payment of Support (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency is now enforcing the support order.

column1: Notice of Change of Responsibility for Managing Child Support Case (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that a local child support agency in a different county is now managing your case.

column1: Notice of Entry of Judgment and Proof of Service by Mail (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the judge made a final order in your case.

column1: Notice and Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Support Order Based on Presumed Income
column4: Tell the judge that the child support amount was based on more money than you were actually making at the time.

column1: Information Sheet for Notice and Motion to Cancel (Set Aside) Support Order Based on Presumed Income
column4: Explains how to tell the judge that the child support amount was based on more money than you were actually making at the time.

column1: Declaration of Obligor's Income During Judgment Period—Presumed Income Set-Aside Request
column4: Tell the judge why the child support amount was based on more money than you were actually making at the time.

column1: Notice to Local Child Support Agency of Intent to Take Independent Action to Enforce Support Order (Governmental)
column4: Tell the local child support agency that you want to file your own request to enforce the support order.

column1: Response of Local Child Support Agency to Notice of Intent to Take Independent Action to Enforce Support Order (Governmental)
column4: Tells you if the local child support agency agrees with your request to enforce the support order on your own.

column1: Statement for Registration of California Support Order (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that your support order was moved (registered) to the court of a different county.

column1: Notice of Registration of California Support Order (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that your support order was moved (registered) to the court of a different county.

column1: Ex Parte Motion by Local Child Support Agency and Declaration for Joinder of Other Parent (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency wants to add the other parent to your case.

column1: Notice of Motion and Declaration for Joinder of Other Parent in Governmental Action
column4: Tell the judge that you want to add the other parent to your case.

column1: Information Sheet for Notice of Motion and Declaration for Joinder of Other Parent in Governmental Action
column4: Explains how to tell the judge that you want to add the other parent to your case.

column1: Responsive Declaration to Motion for Joinder of Other Parent—Consent Order of Joinder
column4: Tell the judge if you agree to be added to the child support case.

column1: Information Sheet for Responsive Declaration to Motion for Joinder of Other Parent—Consent Order of Joinder
column4: Explains how to tell the judge if you agree to be added to the child support case.

column1: Stipulation and Order for Joinder of Other Parent (Governmental)
column4: Parents and the local child support agency tell the court about their agreement to add one of the parents to your child support case.

column1: Findings and Recommendation of Commissioner (Governmental)
column4: Tells you how much child support the temporary judge (commissioner) thinks should be ordered in your case.

column1: Notice of Objection (Governmental)
column4: Tell the judge if you agree with how much child support the temporary judge (commissioner) thinks should be ordered in your case.

column1: Review of Commissioner's Findings of Fact and Recommendation (Governmental)
column4: Tells you if the amount of child support the temporary judge (commissioner) thinks should be ordered is now official or if you will have another hearing in front of a new judge.

column1: Notice of Motion for Judicial Review of License Denial (Governmental)
column4: Tell the judge you need to get your suspended license back.

column1: Order After Judicial Review of License Denial (Governmental)
column4: Tells you if the judge gave you your suspended license back.

column1: Request for Determination of Support Arrears (Governmental)
column4: Tell the judge you want them to decide how much in back support is owed.

column1: Information Sheet: Request for Determination of Support Arrears (Governmental)
column4: Explains how to tell the judge you want them to decide how much in back support is owed.

column1: Notice of Opposition and Notice of Motion on Claim of Exemption
column4: Tell the judge that you don't agree with the request from the other side for money not to be taken from their paycheck.

column1: Order Determining Claim of Exemption or Third-Party Claim (Governmental)
column4: Tells you the judge's decision on the request from the other side for money not to be taken from their paycheck.

column1: Request for Telephone Appearance (Governmental)
column4: Ask the judge for permission to call-in to your court hearing by phone.

column1: Information Sheet—Request for Telephone Appearance (Governmental)
column4: Explains how to ask the judge for permission to call-in to your court hearing by phone.

column1: Notice of Motion
column4: Tells you the local child support agency is requesting new orders in your case.

column1: Clerk Calendar Cover Sheet (For Court Clerk Use Only)
column4: Tells the judge basic information about your case.

column1: Order to Show Cause (Governmental)
column4: Tells you the local child support agency is requesting new orders in your case.

column1: Request for Order and Supporting Declaration (Governmental)
column4: Tells you why the local child support agency is requesting new orders in your case.

column1: Response to Governmental Notice of Motion or Order to Show Cause
column4: Tell the judge and the local child support agency if you agree with the request for new orders in your case.

column1: Proof of Service by Mail (Governmental)
column4: Use this form to prove to the court that you gave the local child support agency and the other side court papers by mail.

column1: Order After Hearing (Governmental)
column4: Tells you the judge's decision after a court hearing.

column1: Short Form Order After Hearing (Governmental)
column4: Tells you the judge's decision after a court hearing.

column1: Minutes and Order or Judgment (Governmental)
column4: Tells you the judge's decision after a court hearing.

column1: Guideline Findings Attachment (Governmental)
column4: Tells you the judge's decision about how child support was calculated.

column1: Advisement and Waiver of Rights for Stipulation (Governmental)
column4: Tell the judge that you agree to give up certain rights (for example, genetic tests) and want your agreement approved without going to trial.

column1: Declaration for Default or Uncontested Judgment (Governmental)
column4: Tells you that the local child support agency is asking for a child support order without your participation because you didn't file an answer.

column1: Joint Petition for Summary Dissolution
column4: Start a simplifed process for divorce if you and your spouse or domestic partner have been married or partners for less than 5 years, do not own or owe very much, do not have children together, do not want spousal or partner support from each other, and you meet all other requirements listed in Summary Dissolution Information (form FL-810) to file this type of case.

column1: Summary Dissolution Information
column4: Explains who can use the simplified process to ask for a divorce, what forms you need to complete, and what steps you need to take to start and finish the case.

column1: Request for Judgment, Judgment of Dissolution of Marriage, and Notice of Entry of Judgment
column4: Tell the court that you filed Joint Summary Dissolution (form FL-800) before January 1, 2011, and that you now want to finish the case.

column1: Judgment of Dissolution and Notice of Entry of Judgment
column4: States the court's decision in a summary dissolution case to end your marriage or domestic partnership. This states the date that you become single and tells each of you to comply with the agreement attached to the judgment.

column1: Notice of Revocation of Joint Petition for Summary Dissolution
column4: Tell the court that you and your spouse or domestic partner want to stop the summary divorce process. This must be done within 6 months after you filed Joint Petition for Summary Dissolution (form FL-800) and other paperwork to start the case.

column1: Request of Minor to Marry or Establish a Domestic Partnership
column4: Tell the court that you are under the age of 18 years and that you and your proposed spouse or domestic partner want a court order to allow you to marry or register a domestic partnership. Give information about your age, education,  and the written consent of each person's parents.

column1: Consent for Minor to Marry or Establish a Domestic Partnerhip
column4: Tell the court that you are the parent of the minor and that you consent to the minor marrying or  establishing a domestic partnership with the proposed spouse or domestic partner.

column1: Order and Notices to Minor on Request to Marry or Establish a Domestic Partnership
column4: States the court's decision (an order) on the minor's request to marry or register a domestic partnerthip. Includes information about what the court considered, the court's findings, a hearing, if any, and provides notices to the minor that are required by law.

column1: Notice of Consolidation
column4: Tells court clerks that the parties have multiple cases in family court, identifies the case number of each case, and combines those case under one primary case number.

column1: Application and Order for Appointment of Guardian Ad Litem of Minor—Family Law
column4: Tell the court why you think the person you named should be appointed to speak on behalf of the child in the case. This includes a section for the person to consent to the appointment and a place for the court's findings and order.

column1: Office of the Family Law Facilitator Disclosure
column4: Tells parties in a family law case that the Family Law Facilitator (FLF) is not their lawyers and that any communication with the FLF is not confidential.

column1: Family Law Information Center Disclosure
column4: Tells parties in a family law case that staff at the court's Family Law Information Center (FLIC) are not their lawyers and that any communication with staff in the  is not confidential.

column1: Notice of Limited Scope Representation
column4: The limited scope attorney tells the court and parties that the attorney will represent the client only on the issues and for the period of time specified in the notice.

column1: Notice of Completion of Limited Scope Representation
column4: The limited scope attorney tells the court and all parties the date that the attorney completed the  agreed-upon tasks for the client. Also explains what the client must do in response to the notice.

column1: Information for Client About Notice of Completion of Limited Scope Representation
column4: Explains what to do if a client agrees or disagrees that the attorney finished the work that each  agreed would be completed in the family law case.

column1: Objection to Application to Be Relieved as Counsel Upon Completion of Limited Scope Representation
column4: Tell the court what services the limited scope attorney did not complete. Also, ask for a hearing and an order that the attorney to continue working on your case until the services are completed.

column1: Response to Objection to Proposed Notice of Completion of Limited Scope Representation
column4: The limited scope attorney tells the court and the client what order the attorney is asking the court to make in response to client's Objection to Proposed Notice of Completion of Limited Scope Representation (form FL-956).

column1: Order on Completion of Limited Scope Representation
column4: States the court's decision (an order) after a hearing that the limited scope attorney did or did not finish the work that the attorney agreed to complete for the client.

column1: Notice of Withdrawal of Attorney of Record
column4: Tells the court and the parties that the attorney is no longer representing a party in the case after the court entered a final judgment of divorce, legal sepration, or nullity.

column1: Request and Declaration for Final Judgment of Dissolution of Marriage
column4: Ask the court to enter a judgment on the date when the judgment could have been originally signed, dated, and filed based on the facts of the case.

column1: Application for Order for Publication or Posting
column4: Ask the court for an order to let you serve the summons in your case by publishing it a newspaper or posting it in a location where the other party will likely see it.

column1: Order for Publication or Posting
column4: States the court's decision (an order) that you can publish or post a summons if you are unable to complete service in other ways.

column1: Proof of Service by Posting
column4: Tell the court when and where the summons was posted and removed, and identifies the person who  papers.

column1: Request to Waive Court Fees
column3: adoption, appeals, custody, child-support, civil, civil-harassment, cleaning-criminal-record, debt-collection, divorce, elder-abuse, eviction, fee-waivers, gender-change, name-change, parentage, probate
column4: Ask the court to let you file papers and receive services without paying court fees and costs because you are getting public benefits, you are a low-income person, or you do not have enough income to pay your basic needs and your court fees.

column1: Request to Waive Court Fees (Ward or Conservatee)
Information Sheet on Waiver of Superior Court Fees and Costs
column3: adoption, custody, child-support, civil, civil-harassment, cleaning-criminal-record, debt-collection, divorce, elder-abuse, eviction, fee-waivers, gender-change, name-change, parentage, probate
column4: Explains who qualifies to ask the court to file papers or receive services without paying court fees and costs. Also explains what forms to use and other important information before you complete the forms.

column1: Request to Waive Additional Court Fees (Superior Court)
column3: adoption, appeals, custody, child-support, civil, civil-harassment, cleaning-criminal-record, debt-collection, divorce, elder-abuse, eviction, fee-waivers, gender-change, name-change, parentage, probate
column4: If you already have a fee waiver order, use this to ask the court to waive other court fees and costs that are not included in that order.

Order on Court Fee Waiver (Superior Court)

column4: States the court's decision about your request to file papers or receive services without paying courts fees and costs.

column1: Order on Court Fee Waiver (Superior Court) (Ward or Conservatee)
Notice: Waiver of Court Fees (Superior Court)
column4: States the court's decision to let you file papers or receive services without paying court fees and costs in your case.

column1: Notice: Waiver of Court Fees (Superior Court) (Ward or Conservatee)
column4: States the court's decision to let you file papers or receive services without paying court fees and costs in your case.

column1: Request for Hearing About Court Fee Waiver Order (Superior Court)
column3: adoption, custody, child-support, civil, civil-harassment, cleaning-criminal-record, debt-collection, divorce, elder-abuse, eviction, fee-waivers, gender-change, name-change, parentage, probate
column4: Use this to ask for a hearing if the court denies your request to waive court fees and costs. Give more information or attach documents about your financial situation.

column1: Request for Hearing About Court Fee Waiver Order (Superior Court) (Ward or Conservatee)
column4: Use this to ask for a hearing if the court denies your request to waive court fees and costs. Give more information or attach documents about your financial situation.

column1: Notice on Hearing About Court Fees
column4: States the court's decision about scheduling a hearing after the court denied your requet for a fee waiver.  If the court sets a hearing, this includes the day, place, and time of that hearing.

column1: Notice on Hearing About Court Fees (Ward or Conservatee)
column4: States the court's decision about scheduling a hearing after the court denied your requet for a fee waiver.  If the court sets a hearing, this includes the day, place, and time of that hearing.

column1: Order on Court Fee Waiver After Hearing (Superior Court)
column4: States the court's decision about giving you a fee waiver. The court complete this after reviewing additional information or financial documents that you showed at the hearing.

column1: Order on Court Fee Waiver After Hearing (Superior Court) (Ward or Conservatee)
column4: States the court's decision about giving you a fee waiver. The court complete this after reviewing additional information or financial documents that you showed at the hearing.

column1: Notice to Court of Improved Financial Situation or Settlement
column4: Tell the court that your financial situation has changed and that you want the court to end or continue the fee waiver.

column1: Notice to Court of Improved Financial Situation or Settlement (Ward or Conservatee
column4: Tell the court that your financial situation has changed and that you want the court to end or continue the fee waiver.

column4: A law enforcement officer uses this to correct an error in a previously issued traffic citation.

column1: Continuation of Notice to Appear
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this when a Notice to Appear form does not have enough space to list all the charges. This can be attached to a Nontraffic Notice to Appear (form TR-120) or a Traffic/Nontraffic Notice to Appear (form TR-130).

column1: Continuation of Citation
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this when the Notice to Appear/Notice to Correct Violation form does not have enough space to list all the charges. This can be attached to a Nontraffic Notice to Appear (form TR-120), Traffic/Nontraffic Notice to Appear (form TR-130), or Notice to Correct Violation.

column1: Automated Traffic Enforcement System Notice to Appear
column4: A law enforcement agency uses this to notify you that your vehicle was photographed in violation of a traffic signal or sign (for example, a red light camera). This form provides information on the charge(s) and your options going forward.

column1: Nontraffic Notice to Appear
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this when you are stopped or arrested for a nontraffic infraction or misdemeanor, but you are released instead of being taken directly to court. This form provides information on the charge(s) and your options going forward.

column1: Traffic/Nontraffic Notice to Appear
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this when you are stopped or arrested for an infraction or misdemeanor, but you are released instead of being taken directly to court. This form provides information on the charge(s) and your options going forward.

column1: Electronic Traffic/Nontraffic Notice to Appear (4 format)
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this when you are stopped or arrested for an infraction or misdemeanor, but you are released instead of being taken directly to court. This form provides information on the charge(s) and your options going forward.

column1: Electronic Traffic/Nontraffic Notice to Appear (3 format)
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this when you are stopped or arrested for an infraction or misdemeanor, but you are released instead of being taken directly to court. This form provides information on the charge(s) and your options going forward..

column1: Notice to Appear and Related Forms
column4: Explains the purpose and format of Notice to Appear forms, and provides templates for law enforcement agencies to use.

column1: Instructions to Defendant
column4: Explains how to challenge a traffic citation in writing without going to court in person (called a trial by written declaration).

column1: Request for Trial by Written Declaration
column4: Ask the trial court to allow you to challenge a traffic citation in writing without going to court in person (called a trial by written declaration).

column1: Notice and Instructions to Arresting Officer
column4: Tell a law enforcement officer that you have requested a trial by written declaration for your traffic citation, and provides the officer with instructions on how to respond. This form is sent to the officer by the court.

column1: Decision and Notice of Decision
column4: States the trial court's decision in the trial by written declaration.

column1: Request for New Trial (Trial de Novo)
column4: Ask the trial court for a new trial (trial de novo) if you are unsatisfied with the decision in your trial by written declaration.

column1: Order and Notice to Defendant of New Trial (Trial de Novo)
column4: States whether the trial court will grant your request for a new trial (trial de novo), and if granted, gives the date, time, and place of the new trial.

column1: Officer's Declaration
column4: A law enforcement officer uses this to explain the facts that support the charge(s) against you in a trial by written declaration.

column1: Agreement to Pay and Forfeit Bail Installments
column4: Asks the trial court to allow you to pay the full amount of a traffic citation in installments instead of contesting the case in court.

column1: Online Agreement to Pay and Forfeit Bail Installments
column4: Ask the trial court to allow you to pay the full amount of a traffic citation in installments instead of contesting the case in court.

column1: Agreement to Pay Traffic Violator School Fees in Installments
column4: Ask the trial court to allow you to pay traffic school fees in installments.

column1: Online Agreement to Pay Traffic Violator School Fees in Installments
column4: Ask the trial court to allow the defendant to pay traffic school fees in installments.

column1: Can't Afford to Pay Fine: Traffic and Other Infractions
column4: Tell the trial court that you cannot afford to pay the fine in your infraction case, and asks for a lower fine, a payment plan, more time to pay, and/or community service.

column1: Can't Afford to Pay Fine: Traffic and Other Infractions (Court Order)
column4: States the trial court's decision in your infraction case regarding your request for a lower fine, a payment plan, more time to pay, and/or community service.

column1: Instruction to Defendant for Remote Video Proceeding
column4: Explains how to ask the trial court to appear by video in a traffic infraction case.

column1: Notice and Waiver of Rights and Request for Remote Video Arraignment and Trial
column4: Ask the trial court for a video arraignment and trial on the same day in a traffic infraction case. This form explains that you give up certain rights when appearing by video, and confirms that you understand this.

column1: Notice and Waiver of Rights and Request for Remote Video Proceeding
column4: Ask the trial court for a video arraignment and trial on separate days in a traffic infraction case. This form explains that you give up certain rights when appearing by video, and confirms that you understand this.

column1: Order: No Travel With Children
column4: Tells you that a judge has made orders to prevent your child from being taken without permission.

column4: Tells you that a judge has ordered that one parent must be supervised (another person will watch and listen) while visiting with their child

column4: Asks a judge to make some information about a child (age 0-18) confidential in the case.

column1: Privacy Protection for a Minor (Person Under 18 Years Old)
column4: Explains how to ask a judge to make information regarding a child confidential.

column1: Order on Request to Keep Minor's Information Confidential
column4: Tells you whether a judge granted the request to keep information about a child (age 0-18) confidential.

column1: Notice of Order Protecting Information of Minor
column4: Gives you notice that information in your court case has been made confidential.

column1: Notice of Order Protecting Information of Minor (Domestic Violence Prevention) (Chinese)
column4: Gives you notice that information in your court case has been made confidential.

column4: Gives you notice that information in your court case has been made confidential.

column4: Gives you notice that information in your court case has been made confidential.

column1: Notice of Order Protecting Information of Minor (Domestic Violence Prevention) (Vietnamese)
column4: Gives you notice that information in your court case has been made confidential.

column4: Use this as a cover sheet for any paper or form you want to file in your case that includes confidentail information.

column4: Tells you if the court has canceled or changed a long-term restraining order.

column1: How Do I Ask to Change or End a Domestic Violence Restraining Order After Hearing?
column4: Explains how to change or cancel a long-term restraining order. A long-term restraining order usually lasts from one to five years.

column4: Explains how you can get ready for your court date for a restraining order.

column4: Explains how you can enforce a restraining order that has been granted by a judge.

column4: Explains which form you should use if you are required to show the court and other side your financial situation.

column4: Ask the court to register a restraining order granted by another state or Canada.

column1: Fax Transmission Cover Sheet for Registration of Tribal Court Protective Order
column4: Use this as a cover sheet if you want to register a restraining order granted by a tribe by fax.

column1: Order to Register Canadian Domestic Violence Protective/Restraining Order
column4: Ask the court to register a restraining order granted by Canada.

column4: Explains how you can ask a judge to renew a long-term restraining order.

column4: Tells you when your court date is for a request to renew restraining order.

column1: Response to Request to Renew Restraining Order
column4: Tell the court and other side if you agree or disagree with ta request to renew a restraining order. This form is filled out by the restrained person only.

column1: Order to Renew Domestic Violence Restraining Order
column4: Tells you that a judge has renewed a restraining order.

column1: Proof of Firearms Turned In, Sold, or Stored
column4: Shows the court that the restrained person turned in or sold their firearms.

column1: How Do I Turn In, Sell, or Store My Firearms?
column4: Explains how you can legally turn in or sell your firearms.

column1: Proof of Enrollment for Batterer Intervention Program
column4: Shows the court that the restrained person enrolled in a batterers intervention program. This form is only used if the restrained person was ordered by the judge to attend this type of program.

column1: Batterer Intervention Program Progress Report
column4: Shows the court whether the restrained person has made progress in the batterers intervention program.  This form is only used if the restrained person was ordered by the judge to attend this type of program.

column1: Order Transferring Wireless Phone Account
column4: Tells a cell phone provider that the court has transferred a phone number to another person.

column1: Attachment to Order Transferring Wireless Phone Account
column4: Use this form if more space is needed to list additional phone numbers that have been ordered to be transferred to a new account.
